# React / Next.js Conventions

## No Hardcoded Text in JSX

All visible strings must come from the locale file. Import the relevant namespace:

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<button>Sign In</button>
<p>Check your email to confirm your account.</p>

// ✅ GOOD
import { AUTH } from '@/locales/en'
<button>{AUTH.ACTIONS.SIGN_IN}</button>
<p>{AUTH.MESSAGES.CONFIRM_EMAIL}</p>
```

## Functional Components with Typed Props

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
export default function ErrorBanner(props: any) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD
interface ErrorBannerProps {
  message: string
}
export default function ErrorBanner({ message }: ErrorBannerProps) { ... }
```

## `'use client'` Boundary

- Default to **Server Components**. Add `'use client'` only when you need browser APIs, event handlers, or React state.
- Never import `lib/supabase/client.ts` in a Server Component.

## Data Fetching — Service Layer vs apiClient

**Server Components** must call `lib/services/` functions directly. They must never make HTTP calls to their own API routes.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — server component calling its own API over HTTP
async function getData(id: string) {
  const res = await fetch(`${process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL}/api/dashboard/${id}`)
  return res.json()
}

// ✅ GOOD — server component calls the service directly
import { getDashboardData } from '@/lib/services/dashboard'
const supabase = createClient()
const { data } = await getDashboardData(supabase, householdId, memberId)
```

**Client Components and hooks** must use `apiClient` from `lib/api/client.ts`. Never use `fetch()`.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — fetch() in a client component
const res = await fetch('/api/households')

// ✅ GOOD — apiClient in a client component or hook
import { apiClient, getErrorMessage } from '@/lib/api/client'
try {
  const res = await apiClient.get<{ households: Household[] }>('/api/households')
  setHouseholds(res.data.households)
} catch (err) {
  setError(getErrorMessage(err))
}
```

## Loading and Error States

Every data-fetching component must handle all three states:

```tsx
if (loading) return <LoadingSpinner />
if (error) return <ErrorBanner message={error} />
return <ActualContent data={data} />
```

## Custom Hooks for Reusable Logic

Extract `useState` + `useEffect` + `apiClient` combos into `hooks/use*.ts`:

```ts
// hooks/useCurrentUser.ts
export function useCurrentUser() {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null)
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true)
  const [error, setError] = useState('')
  // ...
  return { user, loading, error }
}
```

## No `router.push` with Literal Strings

Always use constants from `lib/constants/routes.ts`:

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
router.push('/dashboard')

// ✅ GOOD
import { ROUTES } from '@/lib/constants/routes'
router.push(ROUTES.DASHBOARD)
```

## Accessibility

- Interactive elements need accessible labels (`aria-label`, `role`, or visible text).
- `ErrorBanner` already uses `role="alert"` — follow that pattern for other status messages.
